docs.abstract: Evaluations of state experiments “generally lacked rigor,” and the findings were often kept secret for years, so they were of little use, a government report said.
docs.snippet: Evaluations of state experiments “generally lacked rigor,” and the findings were often kept secret for years, so they were of little use, a government report said.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration is hoping to transform Medicaid by allowing states to test work requirements, premiums and other conservative policies, but a new government report says federal and state officials do not properly evaluate whether such experiments improve patient care or reduce costs.

headline.main: As Trump Pushes Medicaid Testing, the Grading Falls Short

docs.abstract: Congressional Republicans will try once again to undo a requirement in the Affordable Care Act for employers to offer coverage to their employees.
docs.snippet: Congressional Republicans will try once again to undo a requirement in the Affordable Care Act for employers to offer coverage to their employees.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Having wiped out the requirement for people to have health insurance, Republicans in Congress are taking aim at a new target: the mandate in the Affordable Care Act that employers offer coverage to employees.

headline.main: Individual Mandate Now Gone, G.O.P. Targets the One for Employers
headline.print_headline: Health Bill Would UndoAct’s Employer Mandate

docs.abstract: Under current rules, such “short-term, limited-duration insurance” cannot last for more than three months. Under the proposal, the limit would be 364 days.
docs.snippet: Under current rules, such “short-term, limited-duration insurance” cannot last for more than three months. Under the proposal, the limit would be 364 days.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration took another swipe at the Affordable Care Act on Tuesday, proposing new rules that would make it much easier for consumers to buy less expensive health insurance policies that do not comply with coverage requirements of the law.

headline.main: Trump Moves to Relax Rules on Cheaper Health Insurance
headline.print_headline: Trump Moves to Relax Rules on Short-Term Health Insurance

docs.abstract: Alex M. Azar II, the secretary of health and human services, said doctors and hospitals should disclose costs to patients before they were treated.
docs.snippet: Alex M. Azar II, the secretary of health and human services, said doctors and hospitals should disclose costs to patients before they were treated.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Alex M. Azar II, the secretary of health and human services, said Thursday that doctors and hospitals should tell patients how much their care would cost before patients received treatment. And if they do not do so voluntarily, he said, the government may use its leverage to force them to disclose the information.

headline.main: Health Officials Assail ‘Pricing Schemes’ That Gouge Patients
headline.print_headline: Health Secretary Says People Should Be Told Upfront What Treatments Cost

docs.abstract: The National Institutes of Health is helping to develop more cutting-edge drugs. But the agency says its mission doesn’t include evaluating prices, even when the drugs use breakthroughs it patented.
docs.snippet: The National Institutes of Health is helping to develop more cutting-edge drugs. But the agency says its mission doesn’t include evaluating prices, even when the drugs use breakthroughs it patented.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — On Aug. 30, the Food and Drug Administration approved a radical new cancer treatment that harnesses a patient’s immune system to attack tumor cells. The drug, known as Kymriah, grew out of research conducted and supported by the National Institutes of Health.

headline.main: ‘Paying Twice’: A Push for Affordable Prices for Taxpayer-Funded Drugs
headline.print_headline: Health Experts Push to Lower Prices of Taxpayer-Funded Drugs

docs.abstract: Administration officials issued a blunt warning to the board of the Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America, and announced a flurry of actions and plans to coincide with the meeting.
docs.snippet: Administration officials issued a blunt warning to the board of the Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America, and announced a flurry of actions and plans to coincide with the meeting.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When titans of the pharmaceutical industry met here last week at the opulent Mandarin Oriental Hotel, Trump administration officials issued a blunt warning to the chief executives on the soaring prices of their medicine.

headline.main: How the Trump Administration Is Browbeating Big Pharma on Drug Prices
headline.print_headline: Trump Officials Warn Big Drug Companies About Swelling Prices

docs.abstract: A state proposal to limit the number of drugs covered by Medicaid, fiercely opposed by patients and drug companies, has drawn national attention as states struggle to pay for costly new medicines.
docs.snippet: A state proposal to limit the number of drugs covered by Medicaid, fiercely opposed by patients and drug companies, has drawn national attention as states struggle to pay for costly new medicines.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Massachusetts, which led the nation in expanding health insurance coverage, now wants to rein in the growth of prescription drug spending for low-income people on Medicaid, but its proposals have met an icy reaction from patients and drug companies.

headline.main: Massachusetts, a Health Pioneer, Turns Its Focus to Drug Prices. It’s in for a Fight.
headline.print_headline: Massachusetts Is Tackling Drug Cost. It’ll Be a Fight.

docs.abstract: The court cases that the Trump administration has lost on health care have a common theme: Federal judges have found that the administration cut corners in trying to advance its political priorities.
docs.snippet: The court cases that the Trump administration has lost on health care have a common theme: Federal judges have found that the administration cut corners in trying to advance its political priorities.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration is on a losing streak in court cases challenging its efforts to abruptly change health care policy, but the naming of a new Supreme Court justice could alter the trajectory on some of the most controversial cases, from funding Planned Parenthood to mandating contraceptive coverage.

headline.main: A Fatal Flaw as Trump Tries to Remake Health Care: Shortcuts
headline.print_headline: Trump’s Fatal Flaw in Effort to Overhaul Health Care: Cutting Corners

docs.abstract: Medicare health plans will be able to combine medical and social services under a new law that had support from both parties in Congress and the Trump administration.
docs.snippet: Medicare health plans will be able to combine medical and social services under a new law that had support from both parties in Congress and the Trump administration.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Congress and the Trump administration are revamping Medicare to provide extra benefits to people with multiple chronic illnesses, a significant departure from the program’s traditional focus that aims to create a new model of care for millions of older Americans.

headline.main: Medicare Allows More Benefits for Chronically Ill, Aiming to Improve Care for Millions
headline.print_headline: New Law Expands Medicare Benefits Of Patients Fighting Chronic Illnesses

docs.abstract: As drug prices rise to new heights, President Trump wants to require insurers to reduce out-of-pocket costs for Medicare beneficiaries, but critics see his proposals as prohibited interference.
docs.snippet: As drug prices rise to new heights, President Trump wants to require insurers to reduce out-of-pocket costs for Medicare beneficiaries, but critics see his proposals as prohibited interference.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — In his effort to bring down prescription drug prices, President Trump is testing the limits of a law that prohibits the government from interfering in negotiations between drug manufacturers and insurance companies that provide drug coverage to more than 42 million people on Medicare.

headline.main: Trump’s Plan to Lower Drug Prices Tests Limits of the Law
headline.print_headline: Trump Plan to Lower Drug Prices Tests Law on Government Interference
